gious individualisation in a large variety of non-Western and pre-modern scenarios. Furthermore, the volume challenges prevalent views that regard religions primarily as collective phenomena and provides nuanced perspectives on the appropriation of religious agency, the pluralisation of religious options, dynamics of de-traditionalisation and privatisation, the development of elaborated notions of the self, the facilitation of religious deviance, and on the notion of dividuality.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aIndividualismxReligious aspectsxHistory. 0aReligion (General). 0aSelfxReligious aspectsxHistory. 0aSociology (General). 4aIndividualisierung. 4aReligionserfahrung. 4aReligionstheorie. 4aSelbst. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aIndividualisation.  areligious experience.  aself.  atheory of religion.1 aBanerjee-Dube, Ishita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashir, Shahzad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Tov, Asaph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Zaken, Avner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBremmer, Jan N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBremmer, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBueno, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasteigt, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalmia, Vasudha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 